****************************************************

Rebecca Kutler, Jeff Zucker=E2=80=99s onetime heir apparent at CNN, is now
the big boss at MSNBC, where she=E2=80=99ll lead the company into the SpinC=
o wilderness=E2=80=94managing talent, decline, and anxieties along the way.=
 And yet, she=E2=80=99s not only the best person for the job, but perhaps t=
he only one who can do it.

Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Dylan Byers ( https://puck.news/author/dylan-byers/?utm_campaign=3DIn+the+R=
oom+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Three years ago, before the collapse of CNN=E2=80=94before Jeff
Zucker=E2=80=99s trauma-inducing defenestration, David Zaslav=E2=80=99s rut=
hless debt-reduction exercises, and Chris Licht=E2=80=99s reign of terror; =
before the dumbfounding programming forfeitures and precipitous ratings dec=
lines; and before Mark Thompson set out to transform the business into a di=
gital juggernaut (any day now, Mark)=E2=80=94the heir apparent to take over=
 the once-formidable cable news network was a little-known,
then-42-year-old company veteran named Rebecca Kutler. At the time, the ami=
able and well-liked Kutler was overseeing programming for the network=E2=80=
=99s ill-fated streaming science experiment, CNN+.

=C2=A0

Kutler=E2=80=99s eventual ascension may have been apparent only to Zucker a=
nd his inner circle, but as one member of that council told me, =E2=80=9CRe=
becca was the succession plan.=E2=80=9D A young show producer in
the Jim Walton era, Kutler rose as an executive producer under Zucker and e=
ventually took on oversight of content development and contributor recruitm=
ent, launching several new programs along the way. Most notably, Kutler exh=
ibited the same programming creativity and competitive instincts that defin=
ed Zucker=E2=80=99s own golden age of TV news. Said another Zucker confidan=
t, =E2=80=9CJeff had plans for her; he was setting her up to have a big rol=
e.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Alas, life is prone to twists of fate. Shortly after Licht took over CNN, h=
e traveled to Washington, D.C., and met with Kutler to discuss her future a=
t the network. The two initially envisioned an elevated role for Kutler wit=
h a broad mandate that, among other things, would provide direction for the=
 network at a time when it felt rudderless. Several days later, however, Li=
cht called Kutler and, instead, offered her a significantly smaller role
than the one they=E2=80=99d discussed. Whether Licht reneged out of insecur=
ity, suspicion of her Zucker proximity, or a simple change of heart is anyo=
ne=E2=80=99s guess. In any event, Kutler tendered her resignation.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Two months later, Kutler took her talents across town to MSNBC, where she w=
as named S.V.P. of content strategy. The title belied Kutler=E2=80=99s true=
 and almost immediate influence at the network, which began
with oversight of streaming and Jen Psaki=E2=80=99s burgeoning fiefdom, and=
 expanded to include digital, audio, films, dayside programming, and the ne=
twork=E2=80=99s live events business. To the extent that innovation could s=
till happen at a declining linear network freighted with key man risk, it o=
ccurred on Kutler=E2=80=99s watch. Meanwhile, her boss, Rashida Jones, kept=
 the key man (Joe) and women (Rachel, Mika,
Nicolle) happy, capitalized on CNN=E2=80=99s retreat in primetime, notched =
some ratings wins, weathered some P.R. storms (the Ronna mutiny), and hit t=
he speaker circuit.

=C2=A0

Finally, this week=E2=80=94as had long been anticipated ( https://puck.news=
/msnbc-exit-strategies-washington-post-new-executive-editor/?utm_campaign=
=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustom=
er.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=E2=80=94Mark Lazarus, the
NBCUniversal Media Group chairman and prospective C.E.O. of Comcast=E2=80=
=99s soon-to-be-spun-off cable portfolio, a.k.a. SpinCo, announced that Jon=
es was stepping down as MSNBC president and that Kutler would take over as =
interim leader. There were genuine tears at the meeting=E2=80=94from Rashid=
a, Chris Jansing, Stephanie Ruhle, etcetera=E2=80=94and a little too much e=
mphasis on the idea that this had been Rashida=E2=80=99s decision alone, an=
d one she=E2=80=99d only arrived at last week.
(As I reported in December, this was a conscious uncoupling. There=E2=80=99=
s no indication yet where Rashida will end up, though she could probably se=
cure a soft landing as an advisor to a Theo Kyriakou type.) Meanwhile, Kutl=
er very judiciously sought to keep the attention on her predecessor: =E2=80=
=9CToday is really about honoring Rashida,=E2=80=9D she said.=C2=A0

The Reign of Kutler
-------------------

By that point, of course, most MSNBC insiders had already turned
their attention toward their new leader. In truth, Kutler=E2=80=99s =E2=80=
=9Cinterim=E2=80=9D title is itself=E2=80=A6 interim. Presumably seeing wha=
t Zucker saw, Lazarus has expressed a great deal of confidence in Kutler, a=
nd is almost certain to install her in the position permanently. =E2=80=9CS=
he has my backing to make whatever decisions she thinks helps us in coordin=
ation with the rest of you, the leadership,=E2=80=9D Lazarus told MSNBC sta=
ff on Tuesday, =E2=80=9Cand I=E2=80=99m very confident that we have a plan =
to follow our mission
as it has gone on to date, and we=E2=80=99ll be able to advance who we are,=
 and advance our business in our new company.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Of course, in the grand scheme of things, Kutler=E2=80=99s appointment does=
n=E2=80=99t change anything about the long-term trajectory of MSNBC as it v=
entures beyond the borders of the Comcast/NBCUniversal empire and into the =
wilderness. Lazarus has argued that this new, well-capitalized, and mostly =
debt-free
cable company will allow MSNBC to leverage its profits and pursue growth op=
portunities, which will be true for a few years. But as I noted ( https://p=
uck.news/mika-brzezinski-joe-scarboroughs-excellent-adventure/?utm_campaign=
=3DIn+the+Room+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_content=3DIn+The+Room+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F15%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustom=
er.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) back in November, SpinCo=E2=80=99s re=
al fate is likely to involve an eventual sale to private equity, which woul=
d resize the declining assets, cut budgets, and manage the business for cas=
h flow.

=C2=A0

In the meantime, however, Lazarus appears to be putting the network on the =
strongest footing possible. Kutler=E2=80=99s ascension signals real program=
ming ambition at a time when most broadcast and cable networks are simply m=
anaging decline. In the coming weeks, Kutler will hire a new head of newsga=
thering and head of talent and, I=E2=80=99m told, pursue high-profile talen=
t acquisitions.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, Maddow, who=E2=80=99s a few months into her reduced $25 million,=
 one-night-a-week deal, has announced that she=E2=80=99ll return to the net=
work five nights a week for the first 100 days of the new Trump administrat=
ion. This reunion tour might presumably be extended, depending on how much =
she buoys the network=E2=80=99s sagging ratings. In any case, while the net=
work says the low-rated Alex Wagner will return to the 9 p.m. hour after Ap=
ril
30, few inside 30 Rock believe that will happen.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Told the news of Kutler=E2=80=99s appointment, one industry veteran said, =
=E2=80=9CMSNBC is interesting again.=E2=80=9D Not necessarily, but the news=
 will certainly assuage the many (believe me) MSNBC insiders who are fearfu=
l about what the SpinCo move=E2=80=94and the broader decline of the industr=
y, generally=E2=80=94means for their futures, and who have spent the past t=
hree months
wondering aloud whether they should leave the network. Meanwhile, Kutler ha=
s her work cut out for her. MSNBC has lost roughly half of its total audien=
ce since Trump=E2=80=99s reelection, and two-thirds of the demo audience in=
 primetime. And if any truth is self-evident in cable news, it=E2=80=99s a =
lot easier to be a wunderkind than it is to actually be in charge.

