, =E2=80=9CRebecca <em>was</em> the succession plan.=E2=80=9D A young show =
producer in
the <strong>Jim Walton </strong>era, Kutler rose as an executive producer u=
nder Zucker and eventually took on oversight of content development and con=
tributor recruitment, launching several new programs along the way. Most no=
tably, Kutler exhibited the same programming creativity and competitive ins=
tincts that defined Zucker=E2=80=99s own golden age of TV news. Said anothe=
r Zucker confidant, =E2=80=9CJeff had plans for her; he was setting her up =
to have a big role.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Alas, life is prone to twists =
of fate. Shortly after Licht took over CNN, he traveled to Washington, D.C.=
, and met with Kutler to discuss her future at the network. The two initial=
ly envisioned an elevated role for Kutler with a broad mandate that, among =
other things, would provide direction for the network at a time when it fel=
t rudderless. Several days later, however, Licht called Kutler and, instead=
, offered her a significantly <em>smaller </em>role
than the one they=E2=80=99d discussed. Whether Licht reneged out of insecur=
ity, suspicion of her Zucker proximity, or a simple change of heart is anyo=
ne=E2=80=99s guess. In any event, Kutler tendered her resignation.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">Two months later, Kutler took her talents across town to =
MSNBC, where she was named S.V.P. of content strategy. The title belied Kut=
ler=E2=80=99s true and almost immediate influence at the network, which beg=
an
with oversight of streaming and <strong>Jen Psaki</strong>=E2=80=99s burgeo=
ning fiefdom, and expanded to include digital, audio, films, dayside progra=
mming, and the network=E2=80=99s live events business. To the extent that i=
nnovation could still happen at a declining linear network freighted with k=
ey man risk, it occurred on Kutler=E2=80=99s watch. Meanwhile, her boss, <s=
trong>Rashida Jones</strong>, kept the key man (<strong>Joe</strong>) and w=
omen (<strong>Rachel</strong>, <strong>Mika</strong>,
<strong>Nicolle</strong>) happy, capitalized on CNN=E2=80=99s retreat in pr=
imetime, notched some ratings wins, weathered some P.R. storms (the <strong=
>Ronna</strong> mutiny), and hit the speaker circuit.</p><p style=3D"margin=
:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Finally, this week=
=E2=80=94as had long been <a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF=
9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dVYklSMVcyT00yOC1zaE9KRi1MOD0iLCJocmVmIjoia=
HR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvbXNuYmMtZXhpdC1zdHJhdGVnaWVzLXdhc2hpbmd0b24tcG9zdC1u=
ZXctZXhlY3V0aXZlLWVkaXRvci8_dXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPUluK3RoZStSb29tKy0rU1VCU0NSSUJ=
FUlMrJTI4MSUyRjE1JTJGMjUlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1JbitUaGUrUm9vbSstK1NVQl=
NDUklCRVJTKyUyODElMkYxNSUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cd=
TAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJk=
MTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMDA3NzUwfQ/=
a04fb9fbe423e8b13eb3143323d1fcf4dca49bbedfe10695af5e295f6601d534" style=3D"=
text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">anticipated</a>=E2=80=94<strong>M=
ark Lazarus</strong>, the
NBCUniversal Media Group chairman and prospective C.E.O. of Comcast=E2=80=
=99s soon-to-be-spun-off cable portfolio, a.k.a. SpinCo, announced that Jon=
es was stepping down as MSNBC president and that Kutler would take over as =
interim leader. There were genuine tears at the meeting=E2=80=94from Rashid=
a, <strong>Chris Jansing</strong>, <strong>Stephanie Ruhle</strong>, etcete=
ra=E2=80=94and a little <em>too</em> much emphasis on the idea that this ha=
d been Rashida=E2=80=99s decision alone, and one she=E2=80=99d only arrived=
 at last week.
(As I reported in December, this was a conscious uncoupling. There=E2=80=99=
s no indication yet where Rashida will end up, though she could probably se=
cure a soft landing as an advisor to a <strong>Theo Kyriakou </strong>type.=
) Meanwhile, Kutler very judiciously sought to keep the attention on her pr=
edecessor: =E2=80=9CToday is really about honoring Rashida,=E2=80=9D she sa=
id.=C2=A0</p></div>
